Steps to Reproduce:

1. When using RenderTexture to generate an image with width or height greater than 1024 pixel, the pixel shifts slightly, producing a stretched line (the overall size increases about 0.1% relative to the center of RenderTexture).
2. The same behavior doesn't occur even if you use SpriteFrame to convert part of the image to Sprite (In this case originally it did not, but with the test code shown below it worked without any problems).
3. Sprites that are created by CCSprite->create( image bigger than 1024*1024 pixels ) and displayed on the screen seem to have no problem.

Source image of tile is this(tile.png).
![tile](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17924109/30593707-82c08f20-9d86-11e7-986c-f59d51dfb352.png)

What I expect is such this image.(true.png)
![true](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17924109/30593767-a923873a-9d86-11e7-990b-6a1c6c8da9cf.png)

Stretched image is this.(result.png)
![result](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/17924109/30593659-5d158262-9d86-11e7-9d03-1e30c5fa60ce.png)

Test code is here.( in Helloworld::init() )

`

	int tex_width = 1024;	//1024
	int tex_height = 1024;	//1024
	int test_rate = 1;

	int test_size = 64*test_rate;

	int show_num = 1;	//test_num

	// 1. CCRenderTexture

	CCRenderTexture* pRenderTexture = CCRenderTexture::create(tex_width, tex_height);
	pRenderTexture->setPosition(ccp(0,0));
	pRenderTexture->setAnchorPoint(ccp(0, 0));
	pRenderTexture->begin();
	for (int x = 0; x < tex_width / test_size; x++) {
		for (int y = 0; y < tex_width / test_size; y++) {
			CCSprite* pSprite = CCSprite::create("image/tile.png");
			pSprite->retain();
			pSprite->setPosition(ccp(x*test_size,y*test_size));
			pSprite->setAnchorPoint(ccp(0, 0));
			pSprite->setScale(test_rate);
			pSprite->getTexture()->setAliasTexParameters();
			pSprite->visit();
			pSprite->release();
		}
	}
	pRenderTexture->end();
	pRenderTexture->saveToFile("result1.png", Image::Format::PNG, true);
	if(show_num==1) this->addChild(pRenderTexture);

	// 2. CCSpriteFrame

	CCSpriteFrame* pSpriteFrame = CCSpriteFrame::create("image/true.png", Rect(0, 0, 512, 512));
	CCSprite* pSprite = CCSprite::createWithSpriteFrame(pSpriteFrame);
	pSprite->setPosition(ccp(0, 0));
	pSprite->setAnchorPoint(ccp(0, 0));
	pSprite->setScale(test_rate);
	pSprite->getTexture()->setAliasTexParameters();
	if (show_num == 2) this->addChild(pSprite);
	pRenderTexture = CCRenderTexture::create(512, 512);
	pRenderTexture->begin();
	pSprite->visit();
	pRenderTexture->end();
	pRenderTexture->saveToFile("result2.png", Image::Format::PNG, true);

	pRenderTexture = CCRenderTexture::create(1024, 1024);
	pRenderTexture->begin();
	pSprite->visit();
	pRenderTexture->end();
	pRenderTexture->saveToFile("result3.png", Image::Format::PNG, true);

	// 3. CCSprite
	
	pSprite = CCSprite::create("image/true.png");
	pSprite->setPosition(ccp(0, 0));
	pSprite->setAnchorPoint(ccp(0, 0));
	pSprite->setScale(test_rate);
	pSprite->getTexture()->setAliasTexParameters();
	if (show_num == 3) this->addChild(pSprite);
`

I want to create a sprite sheet at startup in order to improve the performance of dot picture games, but it will inevitably look bad because it will be shifted by several dots absolutely.
I also attempted to create the correct sprite sheet by another process, but as I indicated above, even if I read the correct image in my game it was misaligned.

I'm sorry in the text of automatic translation, but please let me know if there is something to know.
